"{\n  \"text\": \"Hey everybody. Fermented beverages like ginger beer here and fermented vegetables like my kimchi here are both fermented foods. Both of them are loaded full of beneficial bacteria, but they don't have the same health benefits, generally speaking, because the bacteria in the fermented beverage is easily neutralized in your stomach, which is an acid bath designed to kind of pre-process your food before it gets to the colon. The roughage that the can that the bacteria is found on with the kimchi is only partially digested. It's not all the way broken down by the stomach. It makes it to the colon intact or at least partially intact. So it gives safe housing for that beneficial bacteria to make it to the colon where it does its work, where it helps digest your undigested food and also teach your bacteria how to do a better job. Tonics, the what they used to call fermented beverages, do settle an upset stomach. They kind of help out with that stomach acid a little bit. So if you got an upset stomach, drink a tonic, but don't expect it to restore your gut health quite as well as fermented that.\",\n  \"sentences\": [\n    {\n      \"text\": \" Hey everybody.\",\n      \"start\": 0.56,\n      \"end\": 1.68,\n      \"duration\": 1.12,\n      \"confidence\": 0.976,\n      \"tokens\": [\n        {\n          \"text\": \" He\",\n          \"start\": 0.56,\n          \"end\": 0.72,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 0.995\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"y\",\n          \"start\": 0.72,\n          \"end\": 0.88,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \" ever\",\n          \"start\": 0.96,\n          \"end\": 1.12,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"yb\",\n          \"start\": 1.12,\n          \"end\": 1.28,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n       